1. Introduction
Campus recruitment is stressful partly because of the uncertainty. Which companies are you actually eligible for? If you are eligible, what are your realistic chances? Most students just guess, and either apply everywhere or miss opportunities they didn't realize they had.
This tool — built in Python for the command line — takes your subject marks, computes your GPA, and then estimates your shortlisting probability for different companies using a heuristic scoring formula. The formula is not a trained ML model. It's a hand-designed scoring system that factors in academic performance, company-specific cutoffs, and some weighting logic drawn from AI search concepts.
The project came out of a coursework requirement, but the problem felt worth actually solving rather than just simulating.

2. Problem Statement
Students going into placement season usually don't have a clear picture of where they stand. They don't know which companies will consider them based on GPA, and even among the ones that will, there's no good way to tell whether they're a competitive applicant or just filling up the candidate pool. So they apply everywhere, waste time on long shots, and sometimes miss the ones where they'd have had a real chance.
This project keeps things simple on purpose. No database, no internet, nothing you can't trace through yourself. The formula is transparent  it takes a student's marks, calculates their GPA, checks it against company cutoffs, and produces a shortlisting probability that's actually explainable. Not a black box.

3. Project Objectives
You enter marks for five subjects. The tool computes your GPA, drops any companies below their minimum cutoff, then scores the remaining ones using a probability formula and sorts them highest to lowest. The output is plain text clean enough to read in under a minute.
The sorting logic mirrors Best-First Search: rather than showing every eligible company in arbitrary order, it surfaces the ones worth applying to first.

4. Technical Approach
4.1 GPA Calculation
The student inputs marks for five subjects (out of 100). The GPA is computed using a simple linear conversion:

GPA = (Sum of Marks) / (Number of Subjects × 10)

This maps a percentage-based score to a 10-point GPA scale, consistent with how most Indian universities including VIT Bhopal calculate CGPA.

4.2 Eligibility Filter
Every company has a minimum GPA cutoff. The tool filters out ineligible ones first, so the probability formula only runs on companies that actually matter for that student.
4.3 Selection Probability Formula (Heuristic)
For each eligible company, the probability is computed as:

P = max(0, min(100, (GPA − MinGPA) × 20 − (Difficulty × 10) + 50))

The probability score has three parts. The gap between the student's GPA and the company's minimum cutoff gets multiplied by 20,  a half-point margin above the threshold adds 10 points to the score. A difficulty penalty subtracts based on how selective the company is (rated 1 to 3, multiplied by 10). And there's a base offset of 50, so a student who just barely qualifies starts at 50% rather than zero.
The final number is clamped between 0 and 100. No 120s, no negatives

4.4 Informed Search (Best-First Ordering)
After scoring, companies are sorted highest to lowest. It's the same logic as Best-First Search: don't start with the longest shots. A student reading the output knows immediately where to focus — the list does the prioritisation for them
